^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Yes, the Law of Total Tricks is particularly useful when partner preempts. For example, if partner opens a weak 2 and you have 3 card support, you should "further the preempt" by bidding 3 (9 tricks with a 9-card fit) even if you have few points. Similarly, with 4-card support you should bid 4.

As I explained before, you can certainly bid game with 3 (or even 2) card support with a good hand, but with a hand not worth bidding game you should raise anyway based on your number of trumps. 

Similarly, if partner opens at 3-level preempt, you should assume a 7-card suit and bid 4 with 3-card support.|
